# Peer-review 

## Introduction

*This part of the homework will focus on the review of Kirchengast, S., & Marosi, A. (2008). Gender differences in body composition, physical activity, eating behavior and body image among normal weight adolescents—An evolutionary approach.* Collegium Antropologicum*, 32(4), 1079–1086. [https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19149211/](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19149211/).* ***Read the full article*** *before answering the questions.* 

## Guiding questions

### Study overview

#### What is the overall research question? Answer in 1-3 sentences.

The overall research question is whether normal-weight adolescent girls and boys differ in body composition (fat mass, fat-free mass) and whether these gender differences are associated with physical activity patterns, eating behavior, and body image. The authors also examine which of these factors independently predicts body-composition measures during adolescence.

#### Briefly describe the study design. Answer in 1-3 sentences.

This was an observational cross-sectional study of normal-weight adolescents (girls and boys aged 11–18 years) from Eastern Austria. Body composition was measured using bioelectrical impedance, and information on physical activity, eating behavior, and body image was collected via structured questionnaires/interviews at a single point in time.

*Focusing on the investigation of body image across genders.*

### Methods for the study of gender differences in body image

#### Which statistical tests are used for the analyses?

They first assessed distributional assumptions using the Kolmogorov–Smirnov test. And, they tested group (gender) differences using Mann–Whitney U tests for quantitative variables and Chi-square tests for categorical variables. 

#### What assumptions do the data need to verify for these tests to be applicable?

For Mann–Whitney U test
	•	Observations are independent.
	•	The outcome is at least ordinal.
	•	Groups should have similar distribution shapes.

For Chi-square test
	•	Observations are independent.
	•	Data are counts in mutually exclusive categories.

#### Does this publication report sufficient information to assess whether those assumptions are verified? Indicate which elements in the text, tables, or figures allow you to assess whether the assumptions are verified – if one or several are missing, indicate how this could be fixed by the authors of the study.

Only partly. The authors state that they assessed normality using the Kolmogorov–Smirnov test and therefore used Mann–Whitney U and Chi-square test.

However, they do not report the Kolmogorov–Smirnov results or show plots that would let readers evaluate distribution shape or outliers. For the Chi-square analyses in Table 2, results are presented as percentages and p-values, but cell counts/expected counts are not shown, so readers cannot assess whether expected frequencies are adequate for the Chi-square approximation.

To improve transparency, the authors could report n per category for Table 2 and provide simple distribution plots.

### Results on gender differences in body image

#### Considering the text and Table 2, report the conclusion made by the authors and whether you think this conclusion is supported. Answer in 2-3 sentences. 
 
The authors conclude that girls reported poorer body image than boys, with a higher proportion of girls describing themselves as unattractive and non-athletic in both age groups, and more girls rating themselves as too thick.

This conclusion is supported by Table 2, which shows large percentage differences between girls and boys for body shape ratings with statistically significant p-values.

## Full review

*Based on the elements provided above, write a review of this article highlighting its strengths and weaknesses in data analysis. Include specific recommendations for improvement where relevant. Your review should be written as a narrative (not bullet points) for an audience of public health researchers, in fewer than 200 words (include a word count).*

Kirchengast et al. examine gender differences in body composition and body image among normal-weight adolescents using a clear cross-sectional design and appropriate use of nonparametric methods when normality was not met. A key strength is that the analysis distinguishes variable types by applying Mann–Whitney U tests for quantitative outcomes and chi-square tests for categorical body-image measures, and the results are presented in an interpretable way (e.g., clear percentage differences and p-values for body image in Table 2).

However, research transparency could be improved. The paper notes that normality was assessed with Kolmogorov–Smirnov tests but does not report those diagnostics or provide distribution plots, limiting assessment of outliers and whether Mann–Whitney results reflect location shifts versus broader distribution differences. For chi-square analyses, Table 2 reports percentages and p-values but not cell counts or expected counts, making it difficult to verify chi-square assumptions and effect magnitude. The authors should report group sample sizes for each category, include effect sizes with confidence intervals, and provide simple plots or diagnostic summaries to support method choices.

