## Visualizing and Summarizing Data

### Contingency Table

*Generate a contingency table of diet by gender.*

```{r}

library(dplyr)
library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)

tab <- nhans %>%
  count(Diet, Gender) %>%
  arrange(Diet, Gender)

tab %>%
  kable(
    format = "latex",
    booktabs = TRUE,
    caption = "Contingency table of Diet by Gender."
  ) %>%
  kable_styling(latex_options = "hold_position")

```

### Probabilities

*Calculate for each gender, the probability of being on a diet. Include measure of dispersion or uncertainty.*

```{r results='asis'}
library(dplyr)
library(tibble)
library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)

diet_yes <- "Yes"  # On the diet group

res <- nhans %>%
  filter(!is.na(Gender), !is.na(Diet)) %>%
  group_by(Gender) %>%
  summarise(
    x = sum(Diet == diet_yes),
    n = n(),
    p_hat = x / n,
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(
    ci_low = binom.test(x, n)$conf.int[1],
    ci_high = binom.test(x, n)$conf.int[2]
  ) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  transmute(
  Gender,
  n,
  `On diet` = x,
  `Probability (95\\% CI)` = sprintf("%.1f\\%% (%.1f\\%%, %.1f\\%%)",
                                     100*p_hat, 100*ci_low, 100*ci_high)
)

res %>%
  kable(
    format = "latex",
    booktabs = TRUE,
    escape = FALSE,
    caption = "Probability of being on a diet by gender (exact 95\\% CI)."
  ) %>%
  kable_styling(latex_options = "hold_position", full_width = FALSE)

```

### Interpretation

*Based on the reported statistics, discuss expectation regarding a potential association between gender and diet practices.*

Based on the reported proportions, males appear more likely than females to report being on a diet (4.4% vs 2.6%). However, the 95% confidence intervals overlap (Female: 1.7%–3.9%; Male: 3.1%–6.0%), suggesting that any true difference may be small and that we should not strongly expect a clear association without a formal hypothesis test.

## Hypothesis Testing 

*Run the appropriate statistical test to compare the occurrence of diets across genders. Include all the steps, from stating the question to explaining the results in your written answer. You can re-use answers from questions above.*

```{r results='asis'}

#Question
#Is the occurrence of being on a diet associated with gender in this NHANES sample?

#Hypotheses
	#	H0: Diet status is independent of gender (same diet prevalence in males and females).
	# H1: Diet status is associated with gender (diet prevalence differs by gender).

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)
library(tibble)

diet_yes <- "Yes"

# Build 2x2 table
dat <- nhans %>%
  filter(!is.na(Gender), !is.na(Diet)) %>%
  mutate(Diet_status = if_else(Diet == diet_yes, "On diet", "Not on diet"))

tab <- table(dat$Gender, dat$Diet_status)

# Convert to a data frame for a clean table
tab_df <- as.data.frame.matrix(tab) %>%
  tibble::rownames_to_column("Gender")

# Chi-square test
chi <- chisq.test(tab, correct = FALSE)

chi_df <- tibble(
  Test = "Chi-square test of independence",
  Statistic = as.numeric(chi$statistic),
  df = as.numeric(chi$parameter),
  p_value = chi$p.value
)

# Output

tab_df %>%
  kable(format="latex", booktabs=TRUE,
        caption="Diet status by gender (counts).") %>%
  kable_styling(latex_options="hold_position", full_width=FALSE)

chi_df %>%
  kable(format="latex", booktabs=TRUE, digits=4,
        caption="Chi-square test comparing diet occurrence across genders.") %>%
  kable_styling(latex_options="hold_position", full_width=FALSE)

```

\newpage
Since p > 0.05, we fail to reject H0 at the 5% significance level. Therefore, there is not strong statistical evidence of an association between gender and dieting in this sample, although the result is borderline and the observed proportions suggest a possible small difference (higher dieting prevalence among males).


